            <!-- Main Content -->
            <section style="line-height: 1.8; font-size: 1.05rem;">
                <h2 style="color: #1a1a2e; margin-top: 50px; margin-bottom: 25px; font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 600; border-bottom: 3px solid #007bff; padding-bottom: 10px;">The Challenge: Preserving DC's Artistic Legacy</h2>

                <p>Art restoration in Washington DC presents unique challenges. The city's climate, with its humid summers and variable weather patterns, can accelerate deterioration of paintings, sculptures, and mixed media works. Additionally, many pieces in DC collections are historically significant, requiring not just artistic skill but also deep understanding of professional restoration ethics and museum-quality standards.</p>

                <p>Our Washington DC facility operates under controlled environmental conditions with professional-grade materials and equipment. Every project follows strict protocols established by restoration industry standards, ensuring that each restored piece meets museum exhibition quality.</p>

                <h2 style="color: #1a1a2e; margin-top: 50px; margin-bottom: 25px; font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 600; border-bottom: 3px solid #007bff; padding-bottom: 10px;">Case Study #1: 19th Century Oil Portrait - Smithsonian Institution</h2>

                <div style="background: white; border: 2px solid #e9ecef; border-radius: 12px; padding: 30px; margin: 40px 0; box-shadow: 0 4px 15px rgba(0,0,0,0.05);">
                    <h3 style="color: #007bff; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 20px; font-size: 1.4rem;">The Project: Water-Damaged Presidential Portrait</h3>
                    <p><strong>Challenge:</strong> A significant 19th-century oil portrait suffered water damage during a museum renovation project. The canvas had developed mold growth and paint layers were beginning to separate.</p>

                    <p><strong>Our Solution:</strong> Our restoration team implemented a three-phase approach:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Stabilization:</strong> Arrested mold growth using controlled drying and anti-fungal treatments</li>
                        <li><strong>Structural Repair:</strong> Relined the canvas using museum-approved adhesives and professional techniques</li>
                        <li><strong>Aesthetic Recovery:</strong> Inpainting damaged areas using reversible restoration paints matched to original pigments</li>
                    </ul>

                    <p><strong>Results:</strong> The portrait was fully restored to exhibition quality and returned to display within 6 weeks. The piece now features enhanced UV protection and environmental monitoring.</p>
                </div>

                <h2 style="color: #1a1a2e; margin-top: 50px; margin-bottom: 25px; font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 600; border-bottom: 3px solid #007bff; padding-bottom: 10px;">Emergency Response in Washington DC</h2>

                <p>Art emergencies don't follow business hours. Whether it's flood damage from a burst pipe, fire damage, or environmental disasters, our Washington DC team provides 24/7 emergency response for art recovery situations.</p>

